The field was uneven in terms of height, there were many canada geese, and the cold weather all combined to make counting additional ones very cumbersome. Needed to go due to distance home and cold.

"Photo evidence to be provided later." - Demond. Spotted by Tarik flying northbound over lake roughly 50 feet from shore. Smaller goose species with all black head, thin white necklace, gray wings, white rear. Atlantic subspecies chosen due to pale belly and proximity towards Branta bernicla hrota's Fall migration flyway.     DM, TS, WG, and AS staked out for BLKI, POJA, REPH, HADU, and other rarities with the straight east winds and dip in temps to 40 degrees. At 9:47am, Tarik saw a smaller goose with an all black head and white necklace flying by and shouted "What the ___ is that?" to which the 3 birders with cameras fired off photos as the bird flew North over the water, slightly above eye-level. Andy was quickest to ID as BRAN. Demond's 276th Cook year bird, just a day after logging the county record CORA. Tarik's 292nd Cook year bird, placing him 2 away from breaking the county record.
Checklist Comments: 15mp E winds with a cool 40 degrees at dawn. It's been a relatively warmer late Fall than typical. While we failed to see Mike McBrien's 2 Pacific Loons from Lincoln Park waters (likely flew over downtown), we ended up with a jaw dropping Brant flyby and putdown in the Rainbow slip.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Winds NNW then slowly shifted to N, will begin another lakewatch in late afternoon as they shift NNE. Awesome bat migration, with individuals streaming over me 5 or so a minute, and hundreds out on the lake. Watched gulls hunt them down as well.

20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.

Mostly lakewatch after chasing Kelly and Dan's SPTO find! SE winds with more S component, mid 50s and cloudy. We chased the SPTO all the way from our Gillson Park lakewatch, 65 minute drive. 291 birds in Cook for Tarik ties the legendary Peter Tolzmann for 2nd all-time!

15mp E winds with a cool 40 degrees at dawn. It's been a relatively warmer late Fall than typical. Tarik invited a few folks to lakewatch at 566 hoping for a critical Black-legged Kittiwake pickup for the Cook Big Year. Demond McDonald, Woody Goss, Tarik Shahzad and (later in the morning) Andy Sigler were present. While we failed to see Mike McBrien's 2 Pacific Loons from Lincoln Park waters (likely flew over downtown), we ended up with a jaw dropping Brant flyby and putdown in the Rainbow slip.

Observation Details: Lifer! Thanks Aaron G for first reporting this bird and following up with even more reports. Thanks Jayne for heading out on your break to help me find it. At the verge of giving up, I scanned the southern breakwall one last time and spotted the immature plumaged bird on the northern tip of that wall. Immediately recognized its heaftier bill and lighter plumage on the cheek area. Unlike the other ducks, it was diving constantly, leading to several minutes of losing and refinding it in my scope, with very poor scope photos due to distance and being uncooperative. Missed it on Sunday, got it today!

Location: Bend of Little Calumet River, Chicago/Riverdale

Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Location: Southeast corner of Wacker and Michigan
Checklist Comments: While looking out of my office in the Wrigley building towards Michigan and Wacker, I saw a compact, medium sized bird flying a few stories below 11 stories towards the intersection. At first I thought it was a pigeon, but the rapid wingbeats and slightly different body shape pointed me towards peregrine. I followed it with my eyes until it landed 60% up on the northeast corner of the building on the intersection where the pin is. I ran to grab binoculars and a few colleagues to show them the bird. The bird perched for a few minutes before diving straight down onto the western sidewalk on Michigan ave below it, flushing a few pigeons. I could not see what was happening based on the angle, and strangely pedestrians didn't seem to flinch in that vicinity. I wonder if it dove but then rerouted mid-air, out of sight from me due to the awkward angle that didn't allow me to cleanly look down Michigan avenue head-on.

Observation Details: Flew right over my car when I was at the red light. Lifer! Proceeded to search in the area for 20 minutes with no luck, wanted photos of the species. I'm guessing they hunkered down somewhere secluded due to the cold. Lighter dove species with black ring behind the neck. Flew at my windshield then over the car, good looks.

Observation Details: Roosting Nightjar species that's richer brown than a nighthawk, bigger head, but not as big as an ultra-rare chuck's would be. Half sleeping in a tree next to the millenium park bean, pretty high up. Other birders who reported this bird after me took great, diagnostic photos. Expected migrant through the county at this time of year but seldom found and reported. I found this bird while carefully scanning trees for early arriving migratory species. Poor photos will be added, all taken with older iphone model. I missed this species at montrose on wednesday since I was out of town and was worried I'd dip on it for my big year. My second ever self found "rarity." Was birding with my colleague Alex B and we were just about to leave! The stars truly aligned. Shared coordinates with birding community.

Observation Details: Crude and conservative estimate, was not counting. Based on count in photos and extrapolating on the multitude of flocks migrating that weren't photographed. Surely a considerable undercount. Most in pulses of 50+ with 3-4 large waves of hundreds of birds. Bulk of birds began 12:20pm and ended by 1:30pm. We noted distant flocks far to our west, most birds right over the cemetery, and a shift of birds to the east of the river around 1:15pm.
Checklist Comments: 9mph NW winds aiming approx 120 degrees SE through the region, low 30 temp, overcast. Sustained conditions following a slight cold dip on 11/26 with west winds that brought considerable SACRs, multiple WHCR, and 2 GOEAs to the county. Thanksgiving Day. Shifted to entrance of west side of cemetery when Scott joined following the GOEA alert.     One of the most epic days on my Cook County Big Year, after being worried that 16 days of nothing following the Brant was a sign that my luck ran out. Hard work pays off.

Observation Details: Large, white, unmistakeable crane species. Digibin photos attached, camera photos tba. Critically endangered crane species with only a few hundred in the wild. Per sources, this crane is individual 16-23, named 'Animal' after the Muppets character. She was on course to fly over cook county but must have gotten confused/lost and put down in Wilmette. She was rescued by government conservation officials and will be safely transported to Wisconsin. So glad this poor bird received help! And what a special lifer!

Checklist Comments: Sunny, mid 70s at start

Observation Details: My 7th or 8th of the year, southbound bird flying right over our heads at 7:16AM, calling titititititi. Larger brown shorebird with decurved bill - not as long as a curlew's. Reported by Max K in discord at 6:55AM and then Mike and I were on high alert, minutes later Mike spots it flying towards us at 7:16AM. Photo of the bird flying overhead.
Checklist Comments: Joined by Mike M a bit after I arrived. So great to meet him! Strong N winds and slightly from E but not enough for what I needed. Indiana got many PAJAs today. WHIM nice bird to always see.

Observation Details: Unmistakeable close view in short flight. Large brownish shorebird with long and slightly upturned bicolored bill. Brown underneath wing ruling out Hudwit. I've documented over 10 shorebird sp. here this Fall and this bird was unmistakeable with my 2-3 second flyby view. Flew from north to south of the pond, following the west side and could not be relocated. Either it left completely or relocated to an area I couldn't see it. More likely the former but based on the way I flushed it, my gut says the latter. It flew low and slow when flushed. I've been trying for a MAGO all year during their peak months and I believed July was going to be my make it or break it. I spent countless hours at montrose beach waiting for one to touch and go. Now I've started checking deadstick for RNPH, WESA, BBSA, BNST, anything else I need for my big year as I gave up on MAGO. No photo and I *might* have merlin audio because it called once and I had it recording and it's saved, listening back I didnt hear anything but will comb through to add more documentation when I have time one of these evenings. I don't bring my camera in because the mud splashes upwards and the first time I came here it splashed into the lens, I have a long lens that hangs pretty low to the ground when slung. After flushing it I immediately ran to the car and grabbed my camera and risked it, trying to refind it for a photo to no avail. Good luck chasers! My bird of the year; I'm in tears.
Checklist Comments: Took a considerable amount of time to try and refind it for a photo and now I'm late to work. When my heart stopped racing I scanned for other rarities but nothing. Shorebird #s and species down from yesterday morning.

Observation Details: Thanks to Tarik S. Phil S refound using T’s scope, noticing orange on the bill. We have photos of bird in flight and foraging.    So ecstatic that the bird stayed for photos after I couldn't refind it for a photo on thursday. Looks like I wasn't a liar! ;) Congrats to all the folks who got this lifer. Risky and dangerous chase for sure.

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Observation Details: At 41.91326 N, -87.31561 W. Bird approached the boat lazily, circled the boat widely a couple of times, during which time it paid scant attention to the gulls near the boat, was chased briefly by one of those Herring Gulls, then headed away from the boat.    Juvenile, generally dark but showing whitish barring on edges of upper wing covert tracks and strongly whitish barring on uppertail coverts.  Pale gray hind collar, two prominent white primary shafts on outer two primaries with other primaries lacking white shafts, strongly barred white and dark uppertail coverts, central tail feather pair with blunt shape and extending notably past remainder of tail.  Underparts predominantly pale in the head and body with broad dark breast band, pale belly, and mottled dark and white posterior underparts. Under side of wings contrasting darker than body with noticeable barring and with whitish panel at base of primaries. Tail dark from below. Undertail coverts with white and dark barring.    Spotted by Tarik Shahzad off port looking towards the bow. For a few moments this smaller seabird made me think it was a Ring-billed Gull. In my head I thought "another Ring-billed following us far out,  very backlit," and then 2 seconds went by before I realized the sun was behind the clouds, meaning the bird itself was darker. Another half-second paying attention to the head and white flash and I started screaming "JAEGER, JAEGER!!!" What a magical big year. Cook Year Bird #282.
Checklist Comments: Shahzad Pelagic 2024-09-22 Leg 4.

Observation Details: Rare but annual migrant on Lake Michigan. When comparing our 3 jaeger species, PAJA is considered the most common and easily viewable from land with the right winds and luck. Bird picked up in Cook County waters without a shadow of a doubt, proceeded into Indiana waters after zipping N to S.    Juvenile bird. Medium sized gull-like seabird with striking, continuous splotch of a white flash on underwings, cinnamon brown body, blaze nape, acrobatic and falcon-like flight style not buoyant or tern-like, not half dark bill but rather 1/3 dark lead me to cross out Long-tailed Jaeger and decide between Parasitic and Pomarine. Compared to POJA, this bird has a relatively smaller, narrower head. Overall less bulky and deep chested than a POJA, this bird has a more uniform pattern and even weight distribution giving it a sleeker look. Per photos and during direct observation, bill seemed thinner than expected on a POJA. In terms of colors, note the bird's blaze of a blonde nape/collar which is big for separating from POJA, on top of it's chocolatey brown and yes, cinnamon-brown plumage captured well with my photos. The tail helps seal the deal here: more pointed central tail feathers shown in photos compared to what POJA's consistently show in their bluntly squared off tail tip. Photos of my bird banking up also show the upper tail quite well for the more PAJA-like covert barring! A lack of a double white flash is not diagnostic for ruling out POJA but notable as well. Reiterating the most critical points which lead me to calling the bird are the nape, body plumage, build, tail (!!!), upper tail coverts in photo of it banking, bill, head size. I was initially caught off guard by the bird's flight style and extensive white flash, but recollecting the sighting, referencing photos and fellow birders (thanks to many folks including Woody, Amar, Simon, Owen, Matthew, Lucas, Mike to name a few), I have confident justification for PAJA and calling it!    How I got the bird: noting the strong N/NE winds, I posted up at the bend of park no.566 with snacks and a dream. It was an incredibly slow day with only pintails moving every half hour, but my birding buddy Andy S emphasized that jaegers and gulls are on different schedules than ducks. With the winds blasting in our faces, waves crashing on the park's rocks leading to water droplets spraying us every few minutes, we handled the monotony by chatting and brief scans of the lake. At approx. 1:28pm, we spotted a dark gull-like seabird blasting North to South at around 10 o'clock directionally from the bend, around 200 yards away, maneuvering over the intense waves. As Andy remarked "Huh, that's interesting" I stumbled out of my chair, grabbing my camera, racing to the edge of the rocks and screamed "JAEGER, THAT'S A JAEGER!!!" Quickly firing off photos and struggling to get focus and balance, the bird had mostly passed us headed South East. Right off the bat, we didn't notice the white flash but instead the thinness of the wings, dark body, slender build, speedy flight, and striking collar of the bird. An incredible encounter for my 283rd Big Year bird. Unforgettable self-find, mythical seabird rarity, only so many state records and apparently a site record if accepted. Photos added with enhanced exposure to assist with details and will submit extensive documentation of RAW and edited files to IORC when I have more time.
Checklist Comments: 20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.

Observation Details: confident getting this down to one or the other and ruling out Pomarine based on size and flight. Minutes after I arrived, I picked up a small, and emphasis on small bodied and thinner winged, dark sea bird absolutely blasting south right over the water, admittedly not as far from shore as I thought in the moment, maybe a half mile out. Breathtakingly fast utilizing the tailwind, agile and acrobatic twisting to show clear and what I am shocked to say was minimal underwing white flash. A more drab toned bird, more grayish brown than rich chocolatey brown I'd expect from a juv PAJA. But to have another juvie LTJA, can't call it. Didn't note tail feathers, the exact dynamics of the white primary shafts, anything about the head of the bird. Of course I left my scope iphone attachment in the car so I immediately switched from spotting scope to my camera and lost the bird. By then it was already nearing the breakwall blasting south. If it was over the horizon I would have likely relocated for distant photo. I could not refind the bird in my viewfinder with intense waves, it flying low over the water, and minimal light. Incredibly difficult following and documenting these birds.
Checklist Comments: Mostly with Josh Engel and so great to meet him. Andy and Al arrived later in morning. Bummed about my jaeger fail and not getting on the grebe earlier. Strong N winds with a decent E component.

Observation Details: Caught views approx 8:15AM, viewing from SE jutting out of tip of point looking 11 o'clock to the N over lake. Noticeably dark bird, smaller than gull it was harassing. Agile flight, making rounds of the gull with obviously faster flight (the gull I presume RBGU based on lighter build than nearby HERG). Birds were distant and backlit, not providing me views of what I hoped to see plumage-wise, 30 second view of the chase and harassment, grabbed my iphone scope attachment and lost the birds. I had later seen 2 different instances of gulls harassing each other on my watch, but this described experience was markedly different in that the sea bird was quick, agile, and smaller than the gull it was bothering. Unfortunately "flashes" not seen.
Checklist Comments: Winds NNW then slowly shifted to N, will begin another lakewatch in late afternoon as they shift NNE. Awesome bat migration, with individuals streaming over me 5 or so a minute, and hundreds out on the lake. Watched gulls hunt them down as well.

Observation Details: Picked up 2:00pm and immediately lost it. Incredibly distant, small, dark gull-like bird with white flashes in wings, agile and speedy flight, sbound, low over choppy waters. Caught at 12 o'clock directionally from bend in cook county waters, watched it speed into Indiana waters.

Spotted by Tarik at (41.78082, -87.25459) as it joined the flock of Bonaparte's Gulls behind the boat heading back to shore. Juvenile bird with distinct upperwing white triangles formed by dark primaries to elbow and grayish back extending to leading edge. Encountered about 40 minutes before sunset while still in Cook. 4th November record in Cook County history, following November sightings in 1953, 1988, and 1994.

Location: Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Observation Details: Rare but annual vagrant to Lake Michigan. Adult Hooded gull species smaller than nearby ring billed gulls with full black hood, white eye arcs relatively thinner than a FRGU's, longer and slightly droopy dark bill relative to a FRGU's, white body, dark gray upperwings, practically jet black primary extension, Dark legs, lack of white primary tips a FRGU would have. Appeared at 4:19pm on the protected beach and lingered until a firework explosion at 5:24pm flushed all of the gulls into the air, many of which left after (probably southbound). Bird was initially spotted by PIPL monitor Sarah V at 7am, Phil S kindly called me and I arrived in 20 minutes, about 90 seconds after the bird flew off. I decided to camp out at the pier starting at 11am in the hopes that with the winds from the SW and hot day incentivizing people to crowd the surrounding beaches, the gull would seek the protected beach as safe refuge again. This species doesn't sit for long periods of time in cook county per records and I missed one this year already. After 5+ hours of sitting in the sun on the pier, flies biting my ankles, and a horrible sunburn, the bird appeared as I was packing up to leave. One last check with my binoculars and my backpack on and I spotted it. Complete disbelief in that moment. Storybook refind!!! Cook year bird #267!

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Winds NNW then slowly shifted to N, will begin another lakewatch in late afternoon as they shift NNE. Awesome bat migration, with individuals streaming over me 5 or so a minute, and hundreds out on the lake. Watched gulls hunt them down as well.

20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.
Winds shifted to 18kt N/NE, prompted lakewatch at 566 north of bend in hopes of jaeger/phalarope/weird gull flyby.

Mostly lakewatch after chasing Kelly and Dan's SPTO find! SE winds with more S component, mid 50s and cloudy. We chased the SPTO all the way from our Gillson Park lakewatch, 65 minute drive. 291 birds in Cook for Tarik ties the legendary Peter Tolzmann for 2nd all-time!

15mp E winds with a cool 40 degrees at dawn. It's been a relatively warmer late Fall than typical. Tarik invited a few folks to lakewatch at 566 hoping for a critical Black-legged Kittiwake pickup for the Cook Big Year. Demond McDonald, Woody Goss, Tarik Shahzad and (later in the morning) Andy Sigler were present. While we failed to see Mike McBrien's 2 Pacific Loons from Lincoln Park waters (likely flew over downtown), we ended up with a jaw dropping Brant flyby and putdown in the Rainbow slip.

Scoping from far south east end of harbor.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Winds NNW then slowly shifted to N, will begin another lakewatch in late afternoon as they shift NNE. Awesome bat migration, with individuals streaming over me 5 or so a minute, and hundreds out on the lake. Watched gulls hunt them down as well.

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Observation Details: Both S to N and on Lake N to S
Checklist Comments: 20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.
Winds shifted to 18kt N/NE, prompted lakewatch at 566 north of bend in hopes of jaeger/phalarope/weird gull flyby.
Overcast, 72 with bit of rain after we left, S winds.     Jaw-dropping CCLO find by Demond McDonald at Park 566. Erick Masias and Tarik Shahzad carpooled to the park in hopes of refinding.

Mostly lakewatch after chasing Kelly and Dan's SPTO find! SE winds with more S component, mid 50s and cloudy. We chased the SPTO all the way from our Gillson Park lakewatch, 65 minute drive. 291 birds in Cook for Tarik ties the legendary Peter Tolzmann for 2nd all-time!

15mp E winds with a cool 40 degrees at dawn. It's been a relatively warmer late Fall than typical. While we failed to see Mike McBrien's 2 Pacific Loons from Lincoln Park waters (likely flew over downtown), we ended up with a jaw dropping Brant flyby and putdown in the Rainbow slip.

Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Checklist Comments: 20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.

First picked up approximately 5:18pm by Phil and Tarik almost simultaneously and viewed for a few minutes migrating North to South on Lake Michigan. Small, more compact and dark birds with striking dark upper and underparts to their wings, black on face contrasting with white when seen in good light, broader wings giving a shorter wing appearance, "bouyant" but my word I'd like to use here would be "undulating" flight patterns while flying down towards the water's surface to presumably forage whilst migrating with speed and intention. Spotted at the 566 lakewatch location safely in cook county waters and viewed for a few minutes as they flew past the imaginary lake border into Indiana. distant but discernable birds seen with favorable lighting, sun slowly setting to the west. Winds strong from N and slightly from East and several rare lake birds spotted in NW Indiana led Tarik to move to this lakewatch spot in the afternoon hoping to nab a SAGU, LIGU, or jaeger that ventured from IN waters. Several BLTE's confirmed in NW Indiana today, part of a larger migration day for them with both time of year and several hundred miles of stretching wind setup. As Phil spotted and called out the birds uniqueness, Tarik had spotted them within the same few seconds, a neat moment. Not bats, as I'd seen hundreds on several days this Fall, and not chimney swifts which have made my heart skip a beat more than once in the past few weeks. Both viewers are experienced with CATE and smaller sterna diving to forage and watched distant RGBUs dive and swoop along the lake, which were unlike our birds.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Winds NNW then slowly shifted to N, will begin another lakewatch in late afternoon as they shift NNE. Awesome bat migration, with individuals streaming over me 5 or so a minute, and hundreds out on the lake. Watched gulls hunt them down as well.

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.

Location: Powderhorn Lake/Burnham Woods Golf Course, Chicago/Burnham

Observation Details: *Rare, annual migrant through the county best seen in Fall with coinciding temperature dips and northwest winds. Flyover headed Southeast, more E than S. Spotted at 11:51am, arrived behind a flock of 45 SACR high in the sky, circled in the sky twice, stopped pursuing, and soared to the SE. 2nd GOEA along the Des Plaines River this Fall, with a 3rd bird spotted by Mike McBrien west of Lincoln Park (North pond presumed).      Presumed juvenile bird based on plumage characteristics. Enormous, dark brown raptor with smaller head and head projection than BAEA, namesake golden nape, white at tail base, white at base of inner primaries and bleeding into base of secondaries. Did not fly with noticeable dihedral as noted in flight descriptions for the species. (Perhaps too slight for me to notice in the moment).     Noting the NNW winds, low 30 temps, and Dan Hayes' comments about significant SACR movement over the Des Plaines River, I decided to head to western Cook for a lottery chance at GOEA. I first posted up at the Oakton College parking lot, but after the first SACR flock appeared to the west of the river, I googled the closest, expansive green space to the west (All Saints Cemetery), and staked out in its eastern portion. Sunroof and windows down, I heard the first flock of SACRs and exited the car checking for WHCR, GOEA, etc. Immediately noticed the flock flying SW with a large, dark raptor high and in pursuit. A RSHA glided passed the raptor, perhaps what saved the SACR flock from further worry by drawing brief attention from the unidentified bird. With the cloudy sky, the only plumage characteristics I initially noted on the bird was its overall dark coloration. After snapping my first photo and checking it in the viewfinder, I saw a hint of white in the remiges, raised my exposure compensation, and snapped several more photos. As the bird soared off, I noted its direction as more easterly than southerly for chasers. In total shock, I consulted a few northside birders and received a resounding affirmative on the GOEA ID, plopped the alert into discord, and began celebrating. Cook County year bird 293, tying the record. And what a way to do it!!!
Checklist Comments: 9mph NW winds aiming approx 120 degrees SE through the region, low 30 temp, overcast. Sustained conditions following a slight cold dip on 11/26 with west winds that brought considerable SACRs, multiple WHCR, and 2 GOEAs to the county. Thanksgiving Day. Shifted to entrance of west side of cemetery when Scott joined following the GOEA alert.     One of the most epic days on my Cook County Big Year, after being worried that 16 days of nothing following the Brant was a sign that my luck ran out. Hard work pays off.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Gray head, dark upperwings getting lighter moving towards the torso, dark, fan-shaped tail.                                           First spotted by Jacob D over northerly island at approx 8:29AM. I drove up from the calumet area and posted up at a lookout next to the museum looking over MP, pin provided by JD. Bird was refound by me at 9:43AM in my bins and lingered for a few minutes before flying between buildings headed north, just west of the aqua building. Gigantic thank you to JD for the initial report, Mike M for the second refind, JD for the recommended lookout location. Unbelievable chase for my big year, cook year bird 278!!!!!!!!!!!!! Unforgettable experience! Pure magic and gratitude!

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.

Location: Southeast corner of Wacker and Michigan
Observation Details: Taken with iphone through binoculars and a window. A bit foggy, cloudy day.
Checklist Comments: While looking out of my office in the Wrigley building towards Michigan and Wacker, I saw a compact, medium sized bird flying a few stories below 11 stories towards the intersection. At first I thought it was a pigeon, but the rapid wingbeats and slightly different body shape pointed me towards peregrine. I followed it with my eyes until it landed 60% up on the northeast corner of the building on the intersection where the pin is. I ran to grab binoculars and a few colleagues to show them the bird. The bird perched for a few minutes before diving straight down onto the western sidewalk on Michigan ave below it, flushing a few pigeons. I could not see what was happening based on the angle, and strangely pedestrians didn't seem to flinch in that vicinity. I wonder if it dove but then rerouted mid-air, out of sight from me due to the awkward angle that didn't allow me to cleanly look down Michigan avenue head-on.

Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Observation Details: *Rare but especially rare in Fall statewide. Cute, gentle looking Sayornis flycatcher from the western continent with gray head, chest, and rufous belly and undertail coverts. Found by Mark Kolasa and I raced to the dunes after getting the notification. Big shoutout to him for finding it, reporting it, and staying on the bird and Jeff for texting me. A much more likely Spring vagrant so I had no hopes of picking this bird up at this point. Year bird 284, a miracle sighting!

Location: Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Observation Details: Found by Demond big thanks to him! Tyrannus flycatcher with silver/gray head, white outer tail feather creating a "line" look on the outer tail feathers, yellow belly and undertail coverts, light throat and chest. White outer tail feather white line is diagnostic from my understanding. Was on my PIPL monitoring shift and Demond gave me a call, I sprinted over and he relayed it was flying over "where the burrowing owl was." I saw it immediately, a robin sized bird flying toward the lake over the dunes and fired off my photos and raised the exposure a bit in post processing to show that I did indeed photograph it. It disappeared shortly after as they typically do. We thought it dropped in the dunes but no one has refound as of 10:15am. Year bird #270!
Checklist Comments: Piping plover monitoring shift. Only 1 chick left :(. Sea Rocket probably left as of last evening and Pippin too.

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Thanks Isoo for the tip!

Location: Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Observation Details: My first ever solo Cook rarity find and report out!    Small sparrow species that was strikingly similar to a male house sparrow except with a rufous crown and a black spot on its light cheek. Associating with house sparrows. Seen well and diagnostically.    Dan and I were taking Ben on his first ever bird walk. Having only two binoculars and not expecting any rarities, I carried the camera and spotting scope around the sanctuary. While teaching Ben about house sparrows at the southeast end of the main trail, he pointed to a huge flock of house sparrows approximately 50 feet away north, down the main path, inquiring whether all of those birds were house sparrows. Not having binoculars on my person, I setup the spotting scope and started scanning, hoping to find an american tree sparrow or dark eyed junco to show him for contrast to the hordes of house sparrows that have consumed the commentary of his first bird walk. In only about a second, I noticed a weird looking brown sparrow in the flock with a spot on the cheek, slightly different size, and different colored head. Having seen this species once before in the parking lot of TNC's Nachusa Grasslands Preserve in April of 2023, I knew it was a eurasian tree sparrow. As I was readying my camera, the birds flushed due to some kind of disturbance not caused by us. I immediately reported the bird to fellow birders but, due to insecurity and confounding factors, was worried to officially "call it." After it was found an hour later and two birders remarked that they saw a "weird" looking house sparrow prior to me, I am confident I saw this bird.  We walked the main path for the remainder of our walk, throwing sunflower seeds to attract house sparrows and scanning for the eurasian, hoping for a photo to no avail.
Checklist Comments: With Dan and Ben. A spectacular surprise and my first solo rarity find for Cook county!

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Observation Details: Continuing find by Demond McDonald. Camera and Digiscoped photos: thanks to Steve Huggins for the scope looks. Gigantic thank you to Demond on the incredible find. Longspur with drabber features than expected LALO, smaller bill, more white in tail, underside of tail's black triangle differently shaped, higher pitched and more bubbly(?) rattle upon reflush.    Demond texted Phil and I photos asking about a Longspur he had flushed and my jaw dropped looking at his amazing flight shots. Immediately noticed drabber features, differently patterned tail than expected on LALO, and a voice in my head telling me that CCLO was seen in Michigan recently. Asked him to plop the photos in bird ID and began racing down to 566 before folks had even confirmed. Woody G, Erick M, Demond M (who stayed to help, legend!) and I reflushed the bird halfway down the gravel path before the bend when entering from the northern end of the park; it flew 50 or so feet down the path and hugged the left side, where Matthew C, Andy S, and Steve H arrived with their scopes. Had to run back home to work or would have stayed for hours with it. A legendary find only weeks after Demond had also found WEME at the same site. 2nd Cook county record and only a handful of records for the entire state. Cook year bird #288, this one is for you, Isoo! 100 times the birder I am. Standing on the shoulders of giants, what a fun adventure!

Location: Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago

Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

Fun day for dabblers! Got Tarik his year bird Surf Scoter, and unexpectedly set the county high count for pintail! Cold front came through last night, and although it only dropped temps into the low 60s, it brought strong NE winds behind it that enabled the duck flight that we got. Winds were 17mph out of the NE from sunrise until they died down at about 10:30. The group consisted of Matthew Cvetas, Isoo O’Brien, Tarik Shahzad, Peter and Andrea Tolzmann, Josh Engel, Mark Ryan, Demond McDonald, and myself. Most of the group had left by 10AM, and around 11AM we were joined by Noah Whiteman for an hour or so. Hopefully the first of many record-breaking days this season.

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).
Lakefront Bird Walk led by Wendy Paulson, co-sponsored by Openlands and the Field Museum.

20mph N/NE winds with notably strong E component right in our faces, 70 degrees, waves splattering on the 566 rocks and wetting lakewatchers every 15 minutes. Target birds were RNGR, SUSC, HADU, LIGU, PAJA, POJA.    Unforgettable day on my Big Year. Strong N/NE winds prompted me to decide on lakewatching the night before and take the day off from work. Erick texted me saying he'll be headed to promontary point to watch with Jacob, so I went there at first light. Nearly 0 movement on the lake (the entire day!), Jacob, Peter and Cameron leaving, and Erick asked about 566, so we headed there after a few hours. Erick left after few hours, Andy Sigler stumbled upon us and joined me for most of the 566 watch. Around 1pm, him and I paused our conversation and remarked at the dark seabird blasting south, and the rest was history. 10 birds from tying the Cook record.
Winds shifted to 18kt N/NE, prompted lakewatch at 566 north of bend in hopes of jaeger/phalarope/weird gull flyby.

Location: 20356–20426 Stony Island Ave, Lynwood US-IL Yellow headed Blackbird Alex H's find (41.5267,-87.5782)
Observation Details: Blackbird species with striking yellow on the face and head. Not complete and thorough yellow like an adult male, so this may be a female or first year male. Associated with red winged blackbirds, starlings, grackles, and cowbirds. First seen by Alex H at the pin in this field last weekend for only a few minutes before taking off. I spent several hours waiting for it to return that day with no luck. I returned the next day for a few more hours and same story. After a work week had gone by, Alex refound the bird in the same general location yesterday morning at 7am; about the same time he spotted the bird last weekend. With the winds and cold front changing after Sunday the 10th's evening, I knew that this morning would probably be my last chance at this particular individual. Important to note that folks did not expect the bird to linger, as this species seldom stays in one place and eBird records in cook county show that it's quite the fickle species to chase. Despite losing an hour of sleep due to daylight savings, I staked out at Alex H's pin for a third time in 7 days before dawn and, just like the two other stakeout sessions, tried picking out a yellowheaded blackbird from flocks of landing and flyby blackbirds. I parked across the road and stayed in the car with my binoculars and camera to not frighten visiting blackbird flocks. After about 20 minutes of waiting, a dozen blackbirds landed in the field and, for a quarter of a second, I saw a flash of yellow! Panicked, I readied my camera and tried focusing on the bird, but it didn't lock on immediately. I held down my shutter knowing that the bird may fly away just as quickly as it arrived, and I was right. I lingered at the location for about 20 more minutes and it actually returned a second time, right above the car in a tree which I checked because I heard red wingeds calling above me (that's how I got the photo from below). Lifer and BIG thanks to Alex H!!!!!!
Checklist Comments: Yellow headed blackbird stakeout SUCCESS!!!!! LIFER! Cook Bird #254, Cook 2024 Year bird #113!

Observation Details: Continuing find by Demond McDonald. Meadowlark species with less white in tail relative to EAME, paler to yellowish malar more indicative of WEME. R= rectrices. R4 partially white, R5 more, R6 mostly white with a bit of brown. Per Pyle guide pg. 633 Icteridae, our bird best matches example D, tail pattern indicative of WEME. Per Sibley, WEME malar is at least partially yellow, like ours. Observations and photos taken at sunset with full sun giving more of a reddish, rufousey look to some photos. Photos TBD from Demond who got the best ones based on his orientation relative to us flushing the bird twice and his skill with camera. All 3 trip attendees got good looks at suspect bird. None of 3 meadowlarks we encountered sang nor called, hence not ruling out Eastern nor Western by sound. We flushed a total of 3 meadowlarks and honed in on this particular one after Demond got quick photos showing it matching the tail pattern from the morning's bird. Phil and Tarik then followed and flushed this particular bird a second time with Demond a bit farther and him getting more shots with the sun at his back. Bird was last flushed near the bend. A big thank you to Demond for the find, for joining Phil and Tarik near sunset to refind, and for the three participants on their teamwork.

Observation Details: A brown, female-plumaged bird (possibly two different individuals?). It obligingly teed up in a tall, isolated tree by Caracol before dropping down and disappearing into the goldenrods and asters.
Checklist Comments: Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Monthly birdwalk led by Wendy Paulson. Although it took some diligence, we eventually cobbled together an 11 warbler species day, great diversity for early October. The other group added Black-throated Green (=12), and I’m almost certain I got a quick glimpse of an Ovenbird (13?).    For me, however, the “bird of the day" was a bat! We noted one flying in from the lake at ~8:15-8:20 am (landing in a large cottonwood by the parking lot, as did another prior to the birdwalk at ~7:10 am), plus a very high-flying bat at 8:20 am (heading in over the city). We then had two more that flew in and landed in a nearby pair of tall cottonwoods (8:37 am), and finally we discovered two perched Silver-haired Bats in a large maple by the ramped observation platform, one of which gave us a stunning close-up. Presumably all 7 bats were Silver-haireds.    A mercurial weather day, it started auspiciously (partly sunny and comfortable), but then became windy and overcast, before the wind abated and it returned to sunny and partly cloudy conditions. Temps felt cooler thanks to the strong N wind (65°F actually dropping to 62°F before creeping back up to 64°F).

Location: stakeout Black-throated Gray Warbler, Elgin, Cook Co. (2024)
Observation Details: Warbler species with a gray back, two white wingbars, white underbelly, black streaks on belly, and a black and white head with a yellow spot on the lores. Rarity from the western part of continental North America. Visiting a private feeder. Homeowner was gracious and kind, inviting some birders to view this rare and lost individual. Checklist delayed to protect the homeowner's privacy. Photos included.
Checklist Comments: Checklist delayed to protect the privacy of the homeowner who was gracious enough to invite folks to see the rare warbler.
